      <field name="fulltext">âClasp me a little longer, on the brink âOf fate! while I can feel thy dear caress; âAnd when this heart hath ceased to beatâOh! think, âAnd let it mitigate thy woe's excess, âThat thou hast been to me all tenderness, âAnd friend to more than human friendship just. âOh! by that retrospect of happiness, âAnd by the hopes of an immortal trust, âGod will assuage thy pangsâwhen I am laid in dust!â Campbell's Gertrude of Wyoming. TO THE SISTERS OF MY FRIEND, THE FOLLOWING LINES ARE AFFECTIONATELY DEDICATED BY ONE WHO WILL ALWAYS FEEL FOR THEM THE REGARD OF A BROTHER. âIt is not only by assuring his disciples that they shall âknow each other,â that our Saviour consoles them; it is by assuring them that they shall be âunited together;â that all their former affections, all their former connection shall return; that the valley and shadow of death obliterates none of their recollection, and diminishes nothing of their love.â Alison. Bath, January 1, 1820. LINES WRITTEN ON TWELFTH NIGHT, 1820. It is the hour when hearts are gay; When smiling Friends their hands unite, And talk of pleasures past away, Anticipating new delight; And many mansions will display The charms of dance and song to-night: Happy and blest will many be, Joy smiles on them,âbut not on me. It is the hour when Lovers meet, When faggots blaze, and tales are told; When all their yearly sports repeat, The sports that charmed our sires of old: And now age claims a cheerful seat, Youth's harmless gambols to behold: Now Old and Young from care are free, Joy smiles on manyânot on me. It is an hour by custom crowned With mirth and music every year; When jests and Christmas games goround, Those games by Time made doubly dear: Now Friendship's kindest accents sound, And all we see and all we hear Are sights and songs of mirth and glee; Joy smiles on manyâbut not on me. It is an hour when some may boast The cheerful breast, the placid brow; But aching hearts now suffer most, And shrink from joys they used to know; The valued Friend so lately lost, By me is mourned more sadly now: With sighs each happy form I see, Joy smiles on othersânot on me. THE END.</field>
